  "prompt": "If India was a part of UNSC would it have been able to ban Masood Azhar without China's support?",
  "response": "If India were a permanent member of the United Nations Security Council (UNSC), it could potentially have more influence in shaping decisions related to issues like the designation of individuals as terrorists. However, the ability to ban or designate someone like Masood Azhar as a terrorist goes beyond just voting power; it also involves diplomatic negotiations, international support, and consensus within the UNSC and its member states.\n\nChina, as a permanent member of the UNSC with veto power, has historically opposed India's attempts to get Masood Azhar designated as a global terrorist by the UN. In theory, if India were a member, it might be able to leverage its position differently and work to build coalitions or alliances to pressure China or other countries for support. Yet, the complexities of international diplomacy, geopolitical considerations, and existing bilateral relationships would still play a significant role.\n\nIn conclusion, while India's membership in the UNSC could enhance its ability to influence such matters, the specific outcome would still depend on the broader geopolitical context and the dynamics of negotiations with other member states, particularly China. Without Chinese support, it would still be challenging to achieve a ban on Masood Azhar, even if India had more formal power in the UNSC.",
